The cruelty of Trump's immigration system is deliberate. It's not a side effect—it's the point. In July, a mother and four U.S. citizen children—constituents of mine—were detained and held in a cell without access to counsel for two weeks. Thanks to public pressure and a lawsuit I supported, the kids were freed but remain separated from their mother who has never been charged with a crime.

I spoke about their story at a shadow hearing focused on Trump's immigration machine.

There are just 11 days left until a government shutdown.

The question is simple:

Will congressional Republicans work with Democrats to protect working families?
Or will they continue driving up costs and slashing health care for the very communities they represent?

I'll work with anyone to make lives better for Oregonians.

Watch this video.

Mimi is a constituent of mine. She testified at a shadow hearing today about caring for four U.S. citizen children who were detained and torn from their parents. Their mother, Jackie, has never been charged with a crime and yet remains in ICE detention. Jackie wrote a note in a coloring book for the kids to hold onto, not knowing if she would ever see her children in this country again.

That’s the cruelty of this system.
I stand with Secretary of State Tobias Read and his effort to protect Oregonians.

Eight months into my term as a U.S. Representative, I understand a simple truth: you can’t legislate from behind a desk. To make informed, effective policy on wildfire preparedness, forest health, and public lands, you must walk the land, sometimes stumble over its roots, and hear directly from those doing the hard work on the ground.

That’s why I’m backpacking 40 miles around Mt. Hood. Over this four-day trek, I’ll meet with Tribal leaders, conservationists, and policy partners to build durable policies that protect Mt. Hood—and all our treasured places—for generations to come.
